Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix},$ $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix},$ and $\mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}.$  Let $H$ be the orthocenter of triangle $ABC,$ and let $\mathbf{h}$ be the position vector of $H.$

[asy]
import three;

size(180);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A, B, C, H;

A = (1,2,3);
B = (5,3,1);
C = (3,4,5);
H = (A + reflect(B,C)*(A))/2;

draw(B--C--A--cycle);
draw(A--H,dashed);
draw(B--H,dashed);
draw(C--H,dashed);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, S);
label("$C$", C, E);
label("$H$", H, W);
[/asy]

Since $\overrightarrow{AH}$ is perpendicular to $\overrightarrow{BC},$
\[\overrightarrow{AH} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} = 0.\]This gives us
\[(\mathbf{h} - \mathbf{a}) \cdot (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}) = 0.\]Similarly,
\[(\mathbf{h} - \mathbf{b}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{c}) = 0\]and
\[(\mathbf{h} - \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) = 0.\]Expanding these equations, we get
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{h} \cdot (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}) &= \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}), \\
\mathbf{h} \cdot (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{c}) &= \mathbf{b} \cdot (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{c}), \\
\mathbf{h} \cdot (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) &= \mathbf{c} \cdot (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}).
\end{align*}Let $\mathbf{h} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}.$  Then these equations become
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}, \\
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -1 \\ -4 \end{pmatrix}, \\
\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}This simplifies to
\begin{align*}
-2x + y + 4z &= 12, \\
-2x - y - 4z &= -21, \\
4x + y - 2z &= 6.
\end{align*}Solving, we find $x = \frac{15}{2},$ $y = -\frac{13}{2},$ and $z = \frac{1}{2}.$  Hence, the orthocenter is $\boxed{\left( \frac{15}{2}, -\frac{13}{2}, \frac{1}{2} \right)}.$

